[30;1m61 | [0m[35mtime (as returned by the :attr:`Environment.now` property). It then calls the[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m:meth:`Environment.timeout()` factory function to create[0m

[30;1m65 | [0m[35mit signals the simulation that it wants to wait for the event to occur.[0m

[30;1m13 | [0m[35mProcesses *request* these resources to become a user and have to *release* them[0m

[30;1m19 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m20 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m21 | [0m[35mSimPy is very flexible in terms of simulation execution. You can run your[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35msimulation until there are no more events, until a certain simulation time is[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35mreached, or until a certain event is triggered. You can also step through the[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35msimulation event by event. Furthermore, you can mix these things as you like.[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m6 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m7 | [0m[35mA simulation environment manages the simulation time as well as the scheduling[0m
[30;1m8 | [0m[35mand processing of events. It also provides means to step through or execute the[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35msimulation.[0m

[30;1m138 | [0m[35m===========[0m
[30;1m139 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m140 | [0m[35mWe just demonstrated two basic methods for process interactions---waiting for[0m
[30;1m141 | [0m[35ma process and interrupting a process. Take a look at the[0m
[30;1m142 | [0m[35m:doc:`../topical_guides/index` or the :class:`~simpy.events.Process` API[0m

[30;1m90 | [0m[35mwaiting for 3 time steps, it interrupts that process.[0m
[30;1m91 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m92 | [0m[35mInterrupts are thrown into process functions as[0m
[30;1m93 | [0m[35m:exc:`~simpy.exceptions.Interrupt` exceptions that can (should) be handled by[0m

[30;1m29 | [0m[35m``run()`` (which is the original ``car()`` process function) and ``charge()``.[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35mThe ``run`` process is automatically started when ``Car`` is instantiated.[0m
[30;1m32 | [0m[35mA new ``charge`` process is started every time the vehicle starts parking. By[0m
[30;1m33 | [0m[35myielding the :class:`~simpy.events.Process` instance that[0m
[30;1m34 | [0m[35m:meth:`Environment.process()` returns, the ``run`` process starts waiting for[0m
[30;1m35 | [0m[35mit to finish::[0m

[30;1m25 | [0m[35mAn important event type is the :class:`~simpy.events.Timeout`. Events of this[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35mtype occur (are processed) after a certain amount of (simulated) time has[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35mpassed. They allow a process to sleep (or hold its state) for the given time.[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35mA :class:`~simpy.events.Timeout` and all other events can be created by calling[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35mthe appropriate method of the :class:`Environment` that the process lives in[0m

[30;1m10 | [0m[35m===============[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35mIf you break SimPy down, it is just an asynchronous event dispatcher. You[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35mgenerate events and schedule them at a given simulation time. Events are sorted[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mby priority, simulation time, and an increasing event id. An event also has[0m
[30;1m15 | [0m[35ma list of callbacks, which are executed when the event is triggered and[0m
[30;1m16 | [0m[35mprocessed by the event loop. Events may also have a return value.[0m

[30;1m58 | [0m[35mresumed, when SimPy processes the Timeout event. The process function also[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35mreceives the event's value (42) -- this is, however, optional, so ``yield[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35mevent`` would have been okay if you were not interested in the value or if[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35mthe event had no value at all.[0m

[30;1m12 | [0m[35mmachines and a number of cars that arrive at the carwash to get cleaned.[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m15 | [0m[35mlimited number of washing machines. It also defines a process for washing[0m

[30;1m80 | [0m[35mtime) into it, the first element in the queue will by definition always be the[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mone with the smallest *t* and the next one to be processed.[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35mHowever, storing *(t, event)* tuples will not work if two events are scheduled[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mat the same time because events are not comparable.  To fix this, we also store[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35ma strictly increasing event ID with them: *(t, eid, event)*.  That way, if two[0m
[30;1m86 | [0m[35mevents get scheduled for the same time, the one scheduled first will always be[0m
[30;1m87 | [0m[35mprocessed first.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m290[0m[34m of [0m[33m883[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m

  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m

   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mone with the smallest *t* and the next one to be processed.[0m
[30;1m82 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m83 | [0m[35mHowever, storing *(t, event)* tuples will not work if two events are scheduled[0m
[30;1m84 | [0m[35mat the same time because events are not comparable.  To fix this, we also store[0m
[30;1m85 | [0m[35ma strictly increasing event ID with them: *(t, eid, event)*.  That way, if two[0m
[30;1m86 | [0m[35mevents get scheduled for the same time, the one scheduled first will always be[0m
[30;1m87 | [0m[35mprocessed first.[0m

[30;1m75 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35mSimPy's event queue is implemented as a `heap queue[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35m<https://docs.python.org/3/library/heapq.html>`_: "Heaps are binary trees for[0m
[30;1m78 | [0m[35mwhich every parent node has a value less than or equal to any of its children."[0m
[30;1m79 | [0m[35mSo if we insert events as tuples *(t, event)* (with *t* being the scheduled[0m
[30;1m80 | [0m[35mtime) into it, the first element in the queue will by definition always be the[0m
[30;1m81 | [0m[35mone with the smallest *t* and the next one to be processed.[0m

[30;1m52 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m184 | [0m[35mProcesses are events, too[0m
[30;1m185 | [0m[35m=========================[0m
[30;1m186 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m187 | [0m[35mSimPy processes (as created by :class:`Process` or ``env.process()``) have the[0m
[30;1m188 | [0m[35mnice property of being events, too.[0m
[30;1m189 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m190 | [0m[35mThat means, that a process can yield another process. It will then be resumed[0m
[30;1m191 | [0m[35mwhen the other process ends. The event's value will be the return value of that[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m311[0m[34m of [0m[33m883[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m

[30;1m57 | [0m[35m- [NEW] A function *step* has been added to the API. When called, it executes[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35m  the next scheduled event. (*step* is actually a method of *Simulation*.)[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35m- [NEW] Another new function is *peek*. It returns the time of the next event.[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m  By using peek and step together, one can easily write e.g. an interactive[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35m  program to step through a simulation event by event.[0m
[30;1m62 | [0m[35m- [NEW] A simple interactive debugger ``stepping.py`` has been added. It allows[0m

[30;1m97 | [0m[35m==================[0m
[30;1m98 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m99 | [0m[35mProcesses had to inherit the ``Process`` base class in SimPy 2. Subclasses had[0m
[30;1m100 | [0m[35mto implement at least a so called *Process Execution Method (PEM)* (which is[0m
[30;1m101 | [0m[35mbasically a generator function) and in most cases ``__init__()``. Each process[0m
[30;1m102 | [0m[35mneeded to know the ``Simulation`` instance it belonged to. This reference was[0m
[30;1m103 | [0m[35mpassed implicitly in the procedural API and had to be passed explicitly in the[0m

[30;1m20 | [0m[35m(``SimPy.SimulationRT``) or something else. You usually had to import[0m

[30;1m188 | [0m[35msuspended and resumed once the event has been triggered. To motivate this[0m

[30;1m4 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m5 | [0m[35mSimPy offers three types of :mod:`~simpy.resources` that help you modeling[0m
[30;1m6 | [0m[35mproblems, where multiple processes want to use a resource of limited capacity[0m
[30;1m7 | [0m[35m(e.g., cars at a fuel station with a limited number of fuel pumps) or classical[0m
[30;1m8 | [0m[35mproducer-consumer problems.[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35mIn this section, we'll briefly introduce SimPy's[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m829[0m[34m of [0m[33m883[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/simpy-4.1.1/docs/simpy_intro/shared_resources.rst[0m
   Pattern: [32m\s(apt|apt\-get|aria2c|arp|ash|awk|base64|bash|bpftrace|busybox|cat|chmod|chown|cp|cpan|cpulimit|crontab|csh|curl|cut|dash|dd|diff|dmesg|dmsetup|dnf|docker|dpkg|easy_install|ed|emacs|env|expand|expect|facter|find|finger|flock|fmt|ftp|gawk|gdb|gimp|git|grep|head|iftop|ionice|ip|irb|jjs|journalctl|jrunscript|ksh|ld\.so|ldconfig|logsave|ltrace|lua|mail|mawk|mount|mtr|mv|mysql|nano|nawk|nc|nice|nl|nmap|node|od|openssl|perl|pg|php|pic|pico|pip|puppet|readelf|red|rlogin|rlwrap|rpm|rpmquery|rsync|ruby|run\-mailcap|run\-parts|rvim|scp|screen|script|sed|service|setarch|sftp|shuf|smbclient|socat|sort|sqlite3|ssh|start\-stop\-daemon|stdbuf|strace|systemctl|tail|tar|taskset|tclsh|tcpdump|tee|telnet|tftp|time|timeout|tmux|top|ul|unexpand|uniq|unshare|vi|vim|watch|wget|whois|wish|xargs|xxd|yum|zsh|zypper)\s[0m
[30;1m55 | [0m[35ma *capacity* when it is created::[0m
[30;1m56 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m57 | [0m[35m    >>> import simpy[0m
[30;1m58 | [0m[35m    >>> env = simpy.Environment()[0m
[30;1m59 | [0m[35m    >>> bcs = simpy.Resource(env, capacity=2)[0m
[30;1m60 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m61 | [0m[35mWe can now create the ``car`` processes and pass a reference to our resource as[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m830[0m[34m of [0m[33m883[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
